Parliament did not support an amendment to release Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the doors to the release of the minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing a disadvantaged deal with Russia for Ukraine on purchasing natural gas.
The judgment is not yet firm, the court of appeal has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code with which the former Prime Minister was convicted was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
226 votes were required for their approval.
