Iranian students are willing to die for their country’s nuclear program.
They formed a human shield.
Several hundred university students formed human shields around nuclear facilities in Iran.
With their gesture they want to express their support for their country’s nuclear program in the face of a possible Israeli attack.
The students began praying at noon on Tuesday before the premises and then chorused slogans of death to the US and Israel.
Several hundred university students formed human shields around the nuclear technology center that works with uranium in the Iranian city of Isfahan on Tuesday.
They want to demonstrate that they are willing to defend their country’s nuclear program with their own lives.
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), in a recent report, found that Iran, according to all indications, is striving to obtain nuclear weapons.
Israel is talking about a possible attack on Iranian nuclear facilities.
The students began praying at noon in front of the nuclear facilities in Isfahan and then launched death slogans against the US and Israel.
In the event of an attack, the aim of which would be to paralyse Iran’s nuclear program, Israeli sources said it would reach not only the Isfahan plant, but also the Natanz facility, where uranium is enriched.
Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner
More than one-third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, where overweight affects 9% of the school population and obesity affects 5%.
Most obese children proceed from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, according to current research.
It is again demonstrated the importance of the environment in which it grows for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as reference.
At the table, obsessive children feed, for example, on candy at least twice as frequently as children from families with normal weight.
For dinner, more than 19% of obese people had dinnered chips the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence."
In families of overweight children there is no custom of sporting, which is applicable to most current families, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and participated in the same nearly 900 children of basic education from all over the Czech Republic.
It was already the second edition of the “Obesity is not a coincidence” program, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and the Unilever company.
So far, more than 12,000 children from 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
Adequate diet and enough family exercise are decisive factors, which make the number of overweight and even obesity children decrease significantly.
“Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five meals daily according to the diet: breakfast, lunch, meal, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet,” one of the survey’s results said.
No breakfast but with dinner buffet
Specialists warn that, in a healthy development, details are also important, which also count, such as having a fixed time for breakfast with the family.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of schoolchildren’s families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, each one has breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to discover that in 10% of households there is nothing to eat.
Breakfast, however, is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The study shows that in families of obese children insane fried potatoes are consumed much more often.
Almost all - regardless of weight - drink daily sweet soft drinks (70%).
As a rule, more than 40% of children surveyed do sports, however, among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Make your diet
The next phase of the study enabled the selected boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
“The dietary preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15, from the point of view of a healthy diet, are far from ideal.”
Among your favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets.
"It is above all alarming the popularity of sweet soft drinks," the study's final report warns.
As the main meal, the palm takes the pasta and follows the bird meat closely.
Practically, children always reject the legumes and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Change to healthy habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive fair information.
“In the control group of the study participants, who filled out the questionnaire after completing the prevention program ‘Obesity is not a coincidence’, there was in many cases a major change in favor of the principles of healthy eating,” the study’s results pointed out.
Attracts attention, for example, to sweet soft drinks, where many children would begin to prefer normal and running water.
Children would also more frequently choose poultry and fish for the main meal on the questionnaire and restrict the consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
