Brand story:
Innovative IBM starts its second century of existence
If someone was looking for a term that would define IBM’s strategy with great accuracy, the most approximate would be “long-term.”
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet has passed a hundred years since its foundation.
The foundation of this long-term figure was laid by the first head of the firm, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many problems in the world can be solved if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his seal, around which the life of the giant future will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began to publish in 1935).
Watson was also the foundation of a carefully raised corporate culture.
