IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted in 1924 – it was originally a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that led to the birth of IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
It possessed inventions such as the famous "log-in clock", which allows to control the entrance and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired his supervisory board.
Flint appointed the head of a competitor company, Thomas J. Watson, to assist him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are supported).
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all kinds of appliances for business, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, turnover doubled by $9 million and began the company’s great expansion across the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after almost forty years occupying the boss' chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "peces", which established the computer standard of that time, came on the market under the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering comprehensive advice and high value-added services.
The strategy IBM has paid for over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, “a smarter planet.”
Its goal is to make a more rational use of technology, although the areas have not yet been planned and the circumstances have not been improved, for example, in terms of transport and city administration.
For the commerce sector, IBM introduced not long ago the "Smart Commerce" platform that allows retailers to manage the entire trading cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 he opened a branch in Czechoslovakia at the time, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague. Also here is a world-famous research team that works with voice recognition.
