How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time in most cases sold travel only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists were therefore on vacation to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after that the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and Czech tourist travel was then quite restricted.
A major paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered travel to the West at that time, but one had to get in the queue with a sleeping bag and spend the night, or have "good acquaintances" with the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people", which could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without the guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The Czechs’ way of travelling has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the vacation in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, that the currently favoured destination, Croatia, was not allowed to travel freely until 1989, because it was part of the Yugoslavia of the time.
In the early 1990s, visa waiver was imposed to travel to Western European neighboring states, leading to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechs, for a long time, didn’t look tired of the west excursions, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was that they took food (conserves, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was rising and with it also average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in travel demand.
With the rise in travel demand, agencies started regularly from 1997 to prepare trips using charter flight connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of getting discounts for the volume of passengers.
At the end of the 1990s, Czechs traveled without a visa to almost all developed countries except the US, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to huge demand, the first direct flight from Czechia to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart every year to distant and hot countries. This winter will fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit nearly 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US removed visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15,000 Czech krones per head on travel abroad, including expenses at the place of stay.
