Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Are Studying You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far-right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was simply another type that aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having carried out a slaughter in Norway in July, which left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time before his attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - just log in to Facebook.
“We realized that it was not so difficult to reach them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British DEMOS study center.
Facebook’s personal information clutch is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy – the way sellers have been using it for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then directed them ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
Upon arriving on Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – all without leaving the office.
“It’s an entirely new way to do an investigation,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not quite surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry about immigration.
“Those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen.”
Demos’s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming an important new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health problems to social trends as expressed in “Likes”, wall messages and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a boom in research, boosting the number of academic papers with the site’s title name to nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn’t approach with a folder on the street.
“Before, when you tried to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You would have to go through the game, and they would never allow you access,” Bartlett says.
"Facebook eliminates all that - you go directly to them."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address social health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and colleagues found that college students who spoke about their drunkenness feats on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent about the topic.
Moreno suggests that student peers, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student post too many status updates with their drunkenness.
“You can’t treat a problem if you can’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno’s co-author and director of the Center for Health, Behavior and Child Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
“We have found a way to identify children at risk that would otherwise not be diagnosed.”
Facebook is also constantly “pinching” its own population for data.
The Site Data Team has compiled statistics on the state of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the middle of the 2010 legislature, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - digital freedom advocates long ago arguing that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for investigation).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – the sacrifice for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
“I don’t think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study conducted with the public Facebook walls of students.
"When it came to them, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research item is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know that part of a user’s profile information and wall messages are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
That’s why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There’s no substitute for entering the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about social – and a lot of social still happens offline.”
