7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview, Shown at a Theatre This Week
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the technology genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find more revealing, in a recently rediscovered Jobs interview that has dusted as the advancement of a series of special projections in the larger markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the business processes and product workflows.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a yonk of flow charts - a man who believed many executives suffered "a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds over the dawns of the personal computer, and sat down for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At the time, it had been just 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for popular Internet adoption.
While a small portion of Cringely’s interview was used on Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transportation.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full copy was discovered on VHS in the director's garage.
This slightly re-published archive material is the foundation of Steve Jobs: The Lost 68-minute interview, which arrives at Landmark cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers – from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking accuracy.
There are also times when Jobs's perfectionism comes to the surface, where it seems impatient due to Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster to the topics or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
One thing is to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring in the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, it went and did.
A quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
Over the years in the business, I always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers they give you invariably are, "Oh, that's just the way it's done."
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs detailed his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Confused by the way the costs were recorded – often starting with a “standard cost” that was done at good eye, and then adjusted to a “variable” – he developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine business costs in detail.
About the joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the “Blue Box” he built with Steve Wozniak – a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make free long-distance calls.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
It describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and you were shouting over the public phone and returning a minute later to the public phone at the next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing—it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking for talk to the Pope, while making his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the U.S. diplomat, the two broke out just before the Pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, to hunt for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phonebook and made a call to him.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, I was the only company I’ve seen at that age and formed my vision of what a company was and how well their employees were treated.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for her.
About improving innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he devoted himself to selling a handful of motherboards, a customer asked him if he could assemble the entire equipment.
Working with just 30 credit days, I had to find out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, remember the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments... they screamed to me that it would take me five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got tired and left and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
About large companies losing strength:
Long before leading Apple’s rebirth, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble on his vision, and lose control of their market share.
“Tell me you’re working at IBM or Xerox, so you’re making better photocopiers and printers, and what?”
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no longer successful.
The sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is this kind of people who end up running the companies and people in charge of the products are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to that position of monopoly rots because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - knowledge of the necessary craft.
That's what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 1990s.
They took the defeat of victory.
About innovation as an artistic expression:
“There’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can't make electrons do, glass does them, robots do them, factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end, it all goes down to taste – it goes down to trying to expose you to the best a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you are doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never been ashamed of stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were accidentally the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computer science, it could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
