How to detect a lie
A glance at the latest headlines tells us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging accusations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses of lying to the other.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been accused of perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “pilled” with an open microphone stating to U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Liing has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made ridicule with his denying quickly rejected by the irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding offences related to cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton as he lied during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps at school and college exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given exam responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere 10 to 200 times.
Many of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers were lying three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Detecting lies, or “localization of lies,” is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: “I have you,” the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades at prestigious universities that conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lies have been rebated.
Liars look in the eyes.
They do not always mutter, buzz, blow or rest.
Neither can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmaske.
A trained lies detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question-forming, and times.
I spent several years surveying scientific discoveries on deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or negotiation management.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies," while women say more "other-oriented lies" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies that they usually say tend to be "normal").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the subject’s usual behavior.
This is called “creating a baseline.”
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes afterwards.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It’s best you know if someone normally hits with the foot all the time so you don’t make unfair accusations when you see him beating his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for misleading, verbal and nonverbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who deceive can freeze the upper body by trying to remember their story, can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a "post-interview drowning" -- that exaggerated breath of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Interrogators often falsely show that the interview has ended just to seek that relief post-interview.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson put his leg to the bottom and used the past time while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her nationally.
People who deceive can also use a distancer language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to be true... even as far as I know... to myself."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
