Climate adversity halts the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez’s management, unemployment and informality in Sinaloa has increased, foreign investment has decreased and the economy has contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, self-denominated change, which generated great expectations regarding advances in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, no growth is observed, however, a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development is recorded.
The low temperatures in February, in addition to causing million-dollar losses for the agriculture sector, limited the chances of the state economy to grow, caused a shrinking of overall economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic drop of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost damages, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares of crops were damaged, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops sinistered were those of vegetables, corn and chicken.
The decline in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady rise in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the rate of state unemployment was increased in the first three quarters of the year from a 1,000 to a 5,000 percent increased in the first quarter of the year.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out since public policy.
“What is being seen is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the effects of a resource restriction legislation passed at the Congress to combat money laundering, and for people who grab dollars illicitly it is not easy for them to work, invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Migration detained
López Cervantes noted that in the rise in unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
“The number of people leaving the state looking for work abroad in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties of entering, and second because entering already have a lot of difficulty in finding work, those people are staying and are demanding work sources here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise,” he said.
Informality
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is exacerbated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the occupied population in the state works without being quoted as a worker before any social security institution.
Along with unemployment and informality, another of the state’s labor lags are the low wages, the entity has the lowest remuneration in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of the Signal workers was, until September, 5,352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7,375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Alongside the decline in economic activity and increase in unemployment, the biggest decline in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years was recorded in 2011, according to the Ministry of Economy from January to June, the state FDI amounted to $630,000,697, representing a decline of 87.74 percent from the $5 billion, $143,312 recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17.280 billion pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
Faced with the scenario of economic contraction, the government of the state requested in July the approval of a credit for 3 billion pesos, the same that would be intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to revive the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2.6 billion pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of the debt in any sector.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of Mario López Valdés’ government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 it lacked the harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the government of the state itself.
“The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensively to regain the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we lacked alignment of everyone’s effort and above all the already synchronized good run of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better.”
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events such as early-year frosts stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
“The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frost, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had.”
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, it was required to encourage the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that it has been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which to redefine the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has be detonated," he said.
Work to do
The President of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a forward-looking vision that better addresses the Government’s efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has been striving to give good results in different areas, there are some progress in economic development but it is important that a long-term programme be developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in conducting public policy.
“There are elements that allow us to say that the government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think the government is aware that there is work to be done,” he said.
