Court validates "analog blackout" in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has undergone in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional disputes that the Senate and the House of Deputies raised against the presidential decree advancing the so-called “analog blackout” from 2021 to 2015, by not gathering the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including Court President Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to concretize the transition to terrestrial digital television.
As a result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was rejected for failing to reach a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft judgment, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and of reservation of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and in admitting the demands, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions in it prepared for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers also decided to dismiss the demand filed by the House of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the president said he did not agree with the draft arguments, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to prepare.
"I also don't think that if it did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector corresponds to the federal executive, who has a constitutional mandate, the rectory of the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, and translates into better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone change, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalization, which involves a decision of public interest, which has not only a technical dimension, "because it encompasses economic, social, political and national security issues."
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic governance of the State, encompassing a group of powers which the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, which in some way invades the sphere of competence of the Congress, since the observance of the laws issued by the Legislature is being provided in the administrative sphere, he assured.
The possibility of a "vote-by-vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data thrown by the PREP the difference between first and second places of the election of governor is just 27 percent, yet not counted the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,000 74 total records.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality as regards this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to the data thrown by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second places of the election of governor is just 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,000 total records.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As will be remembered, Michoacán did not approve his Constitution or his State Electoral Code or his Electoral Justice Act, since the Congress of the State approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for them to enter into force in the present electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication in the deadlines provided in the Law of the Official Journal of the State.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local Legislative Power and called "invalid and illegal" the state president's vote on constitutional reforms, since he has no right to "sanction or veto them."
Interviewed about the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the adoption of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be given in cases where: the results of the records do not match; there is no scrutiny and computation record in the file of the box or not in the possession of the president of the box; or where there are obvious errors or alterations of the records.
In addition, the total counting of the vote received in all election boxes may be made when there is indication that the difference between the alleged winner of the election in question and the candidate who won the second place in the vote, is equal to or less than a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is the express request of the party representative and/or the second coalition that postulated.
The total counting of the vote may also be made if, at the end of the ordinary counting, it is established that the difference between the allegedly winning candidate and the second-placed candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is a express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was second-placed, in which case electoral packages that have been the subject of partial counting will be excluded.
It should be noted that in such a situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and the second place is only 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
