The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
Appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with Italy’s president tomorrow to present the new government facing a crisis that has put the country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italy’s appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with Italy’s president on Wednesday to present the new government facing a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and put the entire eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take over.
Monti said he will present to the president the outcome of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country’s ability to overcome this difficult phase,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “framework is now well outlined,” he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, while Italy fights a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a harsh austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the hit trust in Italy.
Underscoring the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets placed the yield of Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much."
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are meant to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told the press.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in their efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined pressure by warning that a Monti failure would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women’s organizations on Monday.
He will end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was named Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty as to whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescuing Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the eurozone.
Monti said his government should last until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before the election is advanced.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but large parties insist that it should be formed only by technicians, an indication of his repairs to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual distrusts and disagreements between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
