This is an excerpt from the conversation, whose full transcription is on The Nation on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican fans, it’s a dream come true that Pearl Jam is going to play in Costa Rica, are they aware of what their fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far has been great.
I’ve been to Costa Rica only once and on vacation; it’s such a beautiful country and I think we’ll be able to stay there for a few days.
So we’re excited to bring our music there.
I ask you because there is a kind of devotion to the band, fans live intensely the days before.
What do you say to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret it took so long to get there.
Some people even refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add some pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played over the last 21 years happened over the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully that made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really look forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did they discover Costa Rica and its waves to surf?
We have a lot of friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going to surf to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; that’s how we learned, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they have been delivering huge shows with many songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never touched there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best possible show with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's this for?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs and each likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play each night.
