MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Leads Social Security research to discover the gene of obesity in children and youth; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced it is conducting a research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescenthood', which will allow markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialities of the 21st Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population, whether or not rightholders, is invited to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He emphasized that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Occidental) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico Oriental).
Once the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
At World Diabetes Day on November 14, he said that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific questionnaires on food.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
On Saturdays, anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure measurement, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics are applied to all participants (the aim is to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz Lopez noted that this research obeys the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
"Health surveys in 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was a 77 percent increase in obesity in boys and 47 percent in girls; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed," the IMSS specialist said.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population differs from others in their genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translate into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows to detect whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) in the neck and forearm, indicating the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors deliver it in writing to parents, to whom each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases are explained.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic illnesses: sedentaryness, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport rather than walking short distances.
It is also due to the high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary beverages, carbohydrates (tails, bread, pizza, burger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mix with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that send the pavement were answered, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 bumps each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the entire process of construction and maintenance of a pavement was adequate, even the aspth.
In his conference A technological opinion of the bumps, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalts could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has a near solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that the asphalt resistance on the streets is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher noted that Mexico City’s streets are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most surface layers is the asphalt folder, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
When the vehicles are transported and the forces are generated, this allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, abundant, is placed a last layer called rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e. a sand that also bathes in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the tyres of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the way.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also requires having the proper thickness and the material from which it is made should be cared.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the terrain is wet, the water is diffused inside the folder and it is difficult to leave, this causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and therefore the formation of bumps.
In the process of forming a bug, he said, the first to wear is the bearing film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed to the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Researchers explained that vehicle loading is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always be in relation to the vehicle loading and ensure that it is met, to prevent the formation of bumps frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow to repair bumps with ease and without the need to use high temperatures.
