This was the work of the caleno who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano.
A Cali's lophoscope went to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a Cali's CTI lophoscope went to history as the man who confirmed the identity of the top FARC chief: "Alfonso Cano", through the analysis of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists working in the CTI section, that week was the turn of "availability" to Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to stay in the jungle for more than five days to reach the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of the frictional skin, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against Alfonso Cano to Eliazar was warned that he should wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be the man who was heading to the world’s oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to carry the decady card of Guillermo León Saenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team to the site where the corpse was found, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, as it was very different from that he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local peasant, without glasses and much thinner.
But the footprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the card.
His eye didn't fail: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, who was indeed the top leader of the FARC.
In search of the footprint
For a dactyloscopist from the Sijín de Cali, the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
Many people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without margin of error, which can become key in the resolution of crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, the lophoscopists support investigations for crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many criminals present fake bills or have no papers.
We take the fingerprint and search for them in the database.
The investigator said that, in a case of theft, it was his time to remove a piece of wall from a house, because at that place the thief had supported his hand to take out a safe full of jewelry and money.
“The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to get a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint from the whole hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts,” he recalled.
Footprints may also dismiss or reaffirm suspects in murder cases.
They recently found a dead man with bottles of liquor around him.
The investigation determined that a family member could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a footprint on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, he does place him on the scene of the crime.
A fingerprinter at the CTI explained that in the objects "the footprints are taken with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them up.
After this, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
“The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians,” the CTI expert said.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the CSI TV show.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a footprint.
However, if it can be used, if the respective measurement is performed.
