The committee of experts also requests that health professionals be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses assistance at the end of his or her life without fear of facing a complaint.
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not only in cases of cancer.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be regarded as euthanasia and undergo the same procedures.
Other experts expressed reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed their reservations regarding the findings of the expert report of the Royal Society of Canada.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described as "extreme" the position of the experts who sign the report, among other things because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to terminally sick.
“This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and is over 18 years old can ask for help to commit suicide,” said Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also stresses that the authors of the report seem to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value of society.
Now, he adds that “in society, there are labels and limitations.”
Health Law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her “strong opposition” to the findings of the report, which she called a “manifesto in favor of euthanasia.”
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, challenges especially the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
