Austrian
Introduction of a "gold rule" in the Constitution
The large social-democratic/Christian coalition government in power in Austria on Tuesday decided to include in the Constitution a “gold rule” budgetary to reduce the public deficit and thus prevent a possible degradation of Austria’s sovereign rating by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when Austrian public debt reaches 74.6%, a figure far above the ceiling of 60% set by the Treaty of Maastricht, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency was reduced to a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion more euros in interest each year,” said Michael Spindelegger, the Christian Deputy Chancellor for Foreign Affairs.
Austria thus responds to a request from the Brussels Summit to the euro area member countries on 26 October: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in an equivalent-value law.
The arrangement adopted by the Austrian government approaches the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease each year by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP), and from 2017, the federal government’s structural public deficit should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states, as well as communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is that, by 2020/2021, public debt will be reduced under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
