Energy policy:
Facts must be worth more than dogmas.
If there is a topic that can’t be dealt with considering short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it’s energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influences the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting is the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if you consider the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options as a whole.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are seven billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing scarcity of fossil resources will have to be alleviated to continue continuously produce electricity, not forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case either in Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or in Switzerland, which aims solely to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to cite a few examples, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, on the other hand, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island crash.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is occasionally presented as an example, reality goes against such discourse.
The Berlin election will lead to a higher price of electricity, a greater energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, particularly from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
It is important to consider the case of Denmark.
The European champion in the wind sector, from which he gets 30% of his electricity, is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittence of the wind; for this reason, his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the continuity of our energy policy, our neighbors pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would deprive realism of the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of the French refuse to pay and, in fact, do not express opposition in principle to this type of energy, according to the surveys.
Remember that our country’s energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of specialized SMEs in international markets that can create non-relocationable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear power, it would mean the sacrifice of much of these SMEs and the loss of 6 billion euros a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to operate for sixty years, when its manufacturer is planned to collapse?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolic source.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of security.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing power plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our professional teams are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it caused neither consequences for people nor for the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural disasters that killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these progress and cooperation between the security authorities and the French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While all electric actors who want to build a power plant are studying it, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, as it would leave them free way to assume leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan manoeuvres dominate a debate so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "the country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped into the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the Libération newspaper of May 23) proclaiming in the past that France "needs no foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has nearly two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone set Michel Rocard explaining that France "can't take over all the world's misery" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden on French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande is limited to including banalities, indicating that the co-development will allow to solve the “migration problem.”
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally profitable, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of immigration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries.
Limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms jobs.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, particularly those with low skills, pushing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are rather complementary than substitutes for domestic workers and primarily carry out occupations in sectors with lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
Positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthesiologists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive influence on the wages and employment of nationals.
Given the above, Giovanni Peri estimated that a 1% increase in migration flows represents a rise in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that an immigrant who arrives in Germany at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to the average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the growth points that he lacked "with his teeth".
These teeth, which dissuaded immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
Europe invented democracy, it only needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some perhaps believed that, in order for democracy to triumph over its enemies, it would be sufficient to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon the Little, that it was something thought.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not sufficient on its own and can even become an “instrument of oppression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The pallinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this respect, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return from the political sphere, but also the worrying sense of its impossibility, of its inconsistency.
You have to think about this ambivalence to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and disorderly.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a void of the nationalist hole: what choices for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take effect, but a common, full-fledged, quiet and continuous exercise of choices and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we wouldn’t know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that follows the orders of markets and rating agencies, that suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers from humiliation in the international sphere.
We care about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that popular sovereignty regains the steering wheel of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare their future through investments.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
Having struggled for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and by Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Let it be so.
But thinking about it without further political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and lead us to a new dead end.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The interest-driven revolution would not be enough.
This lesson remains applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe on the political level, a true European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, let’s make it European.
