The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the gateways.
Kidnapped at a Niamey restaurant by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers captured the researchers’ interest: one leads to a Nigerian who stayed for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is progress, but we should definitely wait to have more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys foreign financial and intellectual support and is becoming increasingly active,” says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these “supports” had become increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or its operating modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex and the same-style suicide bombs or explosive devices used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pushing Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long regarded the group as a community of illuminated unworthy of interest.
A quick success
Founded in Maiduguri in 2002 around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which in the house means “Western education is a sin”) incites the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the northern Muslim part of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It is politicized and demands a strict respect for sharia, while its militants embark on the struggle against the wicked central government.
The latter focus primarily on churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were especially active and attacks on police stations multiplied.
Abuya’s reaction was, as it usually happens, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 dead were recorded.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, is killed in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern feuds.
Last Christmas, he claims an attack that causes 80 deaths in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacks Abuya, in particular the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the United Nations headquarters became its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, ranging from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, disturbs all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and Al-Shebab’s Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to “share all the information.”
