The Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the banks of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that directly connects underwater Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have turned together the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western Europe network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year to Western Europe through a first 1,224-kilometre pipeline that connects the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is expected to be completed by the end of 2012 that will provide a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, it is already talked about the possibility of building a third tube on the same path.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the land flow through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has achieved greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, given that the project has created a gap between Eastern and West Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that binds us organically,” confirmed François Fillon during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent major contracts in the gas sector are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom managers, numerous at Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, by caution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extreme measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden’s waters, but the project leaders resigned when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state company to permanently settle at sea off its coasts.
“In the event of a failure, we will stop the gas passing in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, as they have predicted junctions that, according to the forecast, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device circulating within the pipeline.
With the shape of a cigar, it is introduced into the interior of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repair.
The circulation of gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, in charge of building and operating the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Then, Gazprom leased the company for a period of twenty-five years renewable, all gas transport capabilities.
“Gazprom will be paid for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been carried out by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and by 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach €7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone takes the risk of expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy pine-planted coast.
Valves, with a height of 4.5 meters, form the exit gate of the gas.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people a taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as if aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the current appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first few years has remained far away, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italy’s borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer’s profile, as the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and culted.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees at its inception, now owns nearly 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of towns, and he has been able to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with Moleskine’s development: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition “Detour” where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard tapes, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer cases... The brand encompasses a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19%, up from 9% for the entire population.
Disheartening?
“No,” says Éric Blanchet, Managing Director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
“The progress made for fifteen years is considerable.
At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
“However, there is still a lot to be done.”
It should be noted that disabled unemployed continue to face numerous obstacles to accessing employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years of age (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished their bachelor’s degree and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that especially make it difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the end of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; people’s mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur for the Cité association noted that the directors surveyed have “a low level of knowledge about disabilities,” with an “excessive representation of wheelchair people, physically impaired or intellectual.”
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"We now reach about 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Managing Director of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishments "submitted to this contribution", as well as the amounts paid out, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 million to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies that own between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their employment, compared with 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
